<DOC><DOCNO> AP880912-0038 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 0149EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     09-12 0318</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,300</SECOND><HEAD>NASA Official Says Shuttle Launch May Take More Than One Try</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The head of the nation's space flight programsays NASA will not launch space shuttle Discovery late this monthunless conditions are virtually perfect for the nation's firstshuttle flight since the 1986 Challenger disaster.   ``We're going to wait until we have it right, and then we'regoing to do it,'' said Rear Adm. Richard Truly, head of the shuttleprogram. ``I think the American people expect that of us and that'swhat we're going to do.''   Truly, appearing on ABC-TV's ``This Week With David Brinkley,said it may take more than one countdown to get the Discovery offthe ground. He said that if two recent successful simulations hadbeen the real thing, a launch would not have taken place because ofweather and winds.   ``I think that when we get do get to a launch date on the latterpart of this month, it wouldn't surprise me at all if it took ustwo or three times to get airborne,'' Truly said.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Prison Population Hit Record Total of 604,824 in June</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government says federal and state prisonpopulation grew to a record 604,824 inmates in June, increasing ata rate that would require 900 new prison beds every week.   The federal Bureau of Justice Statistics reported Sunday thatthe national inmate population grew by 4 percent in the first sixmonths of 1988, with the number of female prisoners increasing by6.7 percent.   California, which added 5,146 inmates for a 7.7 percent increaseduring the period, accounted for 22 percent of the nationwidegrowth in the prison population and housed nearly 12 percent of allfederal and state prisoners, the report said.   The largest percentage increases from Jan. 1 through June 30occurred in Rhode Island, which reported 17.9 percent more inmates.</TEXT></DOC>